When a database stores a large amount of data, it may lead to data duplication (data redundancy) and unnecessary information. To solve this problem, normalization is used.

Normalization is the process of organizing data in a database to reduce redundancy and improve data integrity. It works by dividing large tables into smaller, related tables, so that the data is stored efficiently and duplication is minimized.

Normalization is generally achieved using normal forms.

First Normal Form (1NF)
A table is in the first normal form when:

Each column contains atomic (single) values.
Each record can be uniquely identified (usually using a primary key).

Second Normal Form (2NF)
A table is in the second normal form when:

It is already in 1NF.
All non-key attributes are fully dependent on the primary key and not partially dependent on it.

Third Normal Form (3NF)
A table is in the third normal form when:

It is already in 2NF.
There are no transitive dependencies, meaning non-key attributes should not depend on other non-key attributes, but only on the primary key.
